li>employed and earning over the lower earnings limit of £5,564 a year (in 2012 to 2013)</li>\n  <li>looking after children under 12 and claiming Child Benefit </li>\n  <li>caring for a sick or disabled person more than 20 hours a week and claiming Carer’s Credit </li>\n  <li>working as a registered foster carer and claiming Carer’s Credit </li>\n  <li>receiving certain other benefits due to illness or disability </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;re not eligible if you’re:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>employed and earning less than £5,564 per year</li>\n  <li>self-employed </li>\n  <li>unemployed </li>\n  <li>in full-time training </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Contracting out of the Additional State Pension</h2>\n<p>You can only contract out if your employer runs a contracted out pension scheme. Check with them. </p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re a member of a <a href=\"/workplace-pensions/about-workplace-pensions\" title=\"workplace pension\">contracted out workplace pension</a> you don&rsquo;t contribute to the Additional State Pension for the time you belong to the scheme. </p>\n\n<p>This means that when you retire you either don&rsquo;t get any Additional State Pension or it might be reduced, depending on how long you contracted out. </p>\n\n<p>You and your employer pay lower National Insurance contributions while you contract out. When you retire, you&rsquo;ll get a pension from your employer&rsquo;s scheme. </p>\n\n<p>To contract out you must be:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>earning at least the lower earnings limit of £5,564 a year (in 2012 to 2013)</li>\n  <li>paying Class 1 National Insurance (or treated as paying them - check with your employer) </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Different rules apply if you&rsquo;re a member of a salary-related pension scheme before 6 April 1997. These rights, known as the ‘Guaranteed Minimum Pension’, can&rsquo;t be taken before age 65 (men) or 60 (women). The Guaranteed Minimum Pension will continue to be paid at these ages even when the State Pension age rises.</p>\n\n"},{"web