ance</a> if you&rsquo;ve overpaid.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you continue working, you need to get an Age Exemption Certificate to make sure you don’t pay National Insurance - <a href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kbroker/hmrc/contactus/search.ladv?sr=0&amp;as=1&amp;cs=ISO-8859-1&amp;sc=hmrc&amp;sf=&amp;sm=0&amp;nh=50&amp;ha=34&amp;tx0=49620&amp;fl0=__dsid:&amp;tx1=2037&amp;raction=view\" title=\"contact HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC)\" rel=\"external\">contact HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC)</a> to get one.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/tax-national-insurance-after-state-pension-age/tax-on-your-state-pension-and-other-income","slug":"tax-on-your-state-pension-and-other-income","order":3,"title":"Tax on your State Pension and other income","body":"<p>If your total income from work, private pensions and the State Pension is more than your <a href=\"/income-tax-rates\" title=\"tax-free allowance\">tax-free allowance</a> you&rsquo;ll have to pay tax. Your allowances may change with age.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re getting a private pension or you work, your pension provider or employer takes off any tax due, including tax on your State Pension. This means that you might have more than one <a href=\"/tax-codes\" title=\"Tax codes\">tax code</a>.</p>\n\n<p>If you have to pay tax you&rsquo;ll get a <a href=\"/paye-forms-p45-p46-p60-p11d/p60\" title=\"P60\">P60</a> at the end of the tax year showing how much you paid. </p>\n\n<h2>You&rsquo;re just getting the State Pension</h2>\n\n<p>Your State Pension is paid to you without any tax taken off. If you have no income apart from your State Pension and this is below your <a href=\"/income-tax-rates\" title=\"tax-free allowance\">tax-free allowance</a> you don&rsquo;t have to pay tax.</p>\n\n<p>You usually need to complete a <a href=\"/file-your-self-assessment-tax-return\" title=\"Self Assessment tax return\">Self Assessment tax return</a> at the end of the tax year.</p>\n\n<h2>You have other income</h2>\n\n<p>If you have any other income apart from your State Pension and you&rsquo;re over the tax free allowance, you&rsquo;ll have to pay tax. </p>\n\n<p>If your tax affairs are complicated you might have to fill in a <a href=\"/file-your-self-assessment-tax-return\" title=\"Self Assessment tax return\">Self Assessment tax return</a> (eg if you&rsquo;ve foreign income or a lot of investment income).  </p>\n\n<h3>Employed or self-employed</h3>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re employed, your employer will take any tax due off your earnings and your State Pension - this is called Pay As You Earn (<abbr title=\"Pay As You Earn\">PAYE</abbr> ).</p>\n\n<p>Self-employed people must fill in a <a href=\"/file-your-self-assessment-tax-return\" title=\"Self Assessment tax return\">Self Assessment tax return</a> at the end of the tax year, declaring their overall income, including the State Pension. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can get <a href=\"/pension-credit\" title=\"Pension Credit\">Pension Credit</a> if you’re on a low income, even if you work or get another pension.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>You get more than one pension</h3>\n\n<p>If you get another pension or an annuity that you pay tax on, you pension provider will take off any tax due. They&rsquo;ll also deduct tax due on your State Pension. </p>\n\n<h2>Get your tax code corrected or get a tax refund</h2>\n<p>You can <a href=\"/reporting-your-tax-code-as-wrong\" title=\"get your tax code corrected\">get your tax code corrected</a> if you think it&rsquo;s wrong. </p>\n\n<p>You can <a href=\"/claim-tax-refund/you-get-a-pension\" title=\"claim a tax refund\">claim a tax refund</a> if you think you&rsquo;ve paid too much.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/tax-national-insurance-after-state-pension-age/agerelated-tax-allowances","slug":"agerelated-tax-allowances","order":4,"title":"Age-related tax allowances","body":"<p>As you get older there are allowances that can reduce your tax.</p>\n\n<h2>Increased Personal Allowance from age 65</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re eligible for a Personal Allowance <a href=\"/income-tax-rates\" title=\"allowance amounts\">the amount</a> increases in the tax year of your 65th birthday, depending on your taxable income.</p>\n\n<h2>Married Couple&rsquo;s Allowance</h2>\n\n<p>You can claim the <a href=\"/married-couples-allowance\" title=\"Married Couple's Allowance\">Married Couple&rsquo;s Allowance</a> if you&rsquo;re married or in a civil partnership and at least one partner was born before 6 April 1935. It gets taken off your tax bill - the amount that&rsquo;s deducted depends on your income. </p>\n\n<h2>Maintenance Payments Relief</h2>\n\n<p>You can get an allowance to reduce your tax bill for maintenance payments you make to an ex-spouse or civil partner if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you or they were born before 6 April 1935</li>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re separated or divorced and you&rsquo;re making payments under a court order</li>\n  <li>the payments are for the maintenance of your ex-partner (as long as they haven&rsquo;t re-married or formed a new civil partnership) or your children are under 21</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>How much you can get</h3>\n\n<p>For the 2012 to 2013 tax year Maintenance Payments Relief can reduce your tax bill by the lower of the following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>£296 - where you make maintenance payments of £2,960 or more a year</li>\n  <li>10% of the money you&rsquo;ve actually paid - where you make payments of less than £2,960 a year</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>How to claim</h3>\n\n<p>You can claim Maintenance Payments Relief by <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kbroker/hmrc/contactus/search.ladv?sr=0&amp;as=1&amp;cs=ISO-8859-1&amp;sc=hmrc&amp;sf=&amp;sm=0&amp;nh=50&amp;ha=34&amp;tx0=49612&amp;fl0=__dsid:&amp;tx1=2037&amp;raction=view\" title=\"contacting HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC)\">contacting HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>).</a></p